TY  - JOUR
AU  - Kirman, Alan
T1  - Ants, Rationality, and Recruitment*
PY  - 1993
Y1  - 1993/02/01
DO  - 10.2307/2118498
JO  - The Quarterly Journal of Economics
JA  - Q J Econ
VL  - 108
IS  - 1
SP  - 137
EP  - 156
SN  - 0033-5533
AB  - This paper offers an explanation of behavior that puzzled entomologists and economists. Ants, faced with two identical food sources, were observed to concentrate more on one of these, but after a period they would turn their attention to the other. The same phenomenon has been observed in humans choosing between restaurants. After discussing the nature of foraging and recruitment behavior in ants, a simple model of stochastic recruitment is suggested. This explains the “herding” and “epidemics” described in the literature on financial markets as corresponding to the equilibrium distribution of a stochastic process rather than to switching between multiple equilibria.
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.2307/2118498
ER  - 



